inst or alienating people of other faiths. Even as a ruling party in Turkey has set out to undercut the movement, its international influence continues to grow and attract followers who are devoted to service. The scholars whose work appears in this book represent a variety of disciplines, faiths, and nations and offer a wide range of narratives, analyses, and critiques. This title moves beyond mere introduction, analyzing Hizmet and the manifestations of this interfaith movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIslamic sectszTurkey. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  afethullah gulen.  agulen hareketi.  agulen movement.  agulenist schools in america.  agulenists.  ahizmet.  ainterfaith dialogue.  aislam christian relations.  aislam.  aislamic mysticism.  aislamic women.  alate ottoman religious movements.  amuslim christian relations.  apolitical islam.  areligion in turkey.  areligious education.  areligious ethics.  areligious fundamentalism.  areligious service.  asecularization.  asocially conscious islam.  asufi traditions.  aturkish muslims.  awomen and hismet.1 aAppleby, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Phyllis E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindley, Carter Vaughn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGage, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermansen, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarty, Martin E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarty, Martin E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRausch, Margaret